 in this way and will be a valuable resource for those studying policy processes at both undergraduate and post-graduate levels. Mixing collectively written chapters with individual case studies of policies and practices, the book provides a powerful and productive introduction to rethinking policy studies through translation. It ends with a commitment to the possibilities of thinking and doing ‘policy otherwise’.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSocial policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aBainton, Dave, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBainton, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLendvai, Noémi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLendvai, Noémi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStubbs, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Complete eBook-Package 2015z97831111964280 cprintz978144731337340uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447313380?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447313380423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447313380/original  a978-3-11-119642-8  Bristol University Press Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles